    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1951-12-17T07:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1951-12-17T07:00:00-05:00" n="845"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d845">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">795.00/12–1751: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Ambassador in the United Kingdom</hi> (<persName
                        type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Gifford</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#left">
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">top secret</hi>
                    </seg>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">London</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1951-12-17T12:00:00+00:00"
                            >December 17, 1951—noon.</date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>2753. <gloss target="#t_Deptel1">Deptel</gloss> 2931, December 14. I saw Eden
                    last evening just before his departure for Paris and found he had not yet heard
                    of Secretary’s conversation with Franks. Strang<note n="1" xml:id="d845fn1">Sir
                        William Strang, Permanent Under Secretary of State, British Foreign
                        Office.</note> who was present said Foreign Office agreed with our view that
                    a statement would be necessary no <pb facs="1369" n="1353" xml:id="pg_1353"/>
                    matter what armistice terms evolved. He was also optimistic re possibility
                    working out mutually agreeable wording for last paragraph and will await
                    Department’s suggestions. Eden’s only comment was that as memo quoted <gloss
                        target="#t_Embtel1">Embtel</gloss> 2709, December 12, had been approved by
                    Cabinet, any amendments would also need Cabinet action.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Gifford</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
